\par\par \b \uc2  Are today's events bad for us? \b0\par\par\uc2 984 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 July 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  6 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Fauzi Ichsan, Gobal Markets Economist, Standard Chartered Bank, Jakarta, Fauzi.Ichsan@id.standardchartered.com \par \par \uc2  As accounting scandals rock the United States, sending the New York stock market into a tailspin, some \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  analysts are now predicting "gloom and doom" for Indonesia. Their analysis is pretty straightforward. \par \par \uc2  Americans love to spend on credit and they generally do not mind borrowing as long as the values of their assets, their houses and company shares, are going up. Now, the analysis goes, crashing U.S. share markets will make Americans reluctant to borrow and spend more because their company shares are diving in value. \par \par \uc2  A decrease in U.S. domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  will then restrict its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Because the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  generates around 40 percent of the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , a stagnant U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will surely keep the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including Indonesia's, stagnant too. \par \par \uc2  True, the fall of the U.S. share markets might make Americans spend less. But U.S. company shares were highly "overvalued" in the first place. Even now, prices of U.S. company shares are still relatively expensive and can still fall. \par \par \uc2  For example, the U.S. S&P 500 companies have a price-to-earnings per share ratio (PE ratio) of around 33. This means the average share price of the largest 500 US companies is 33 times its earning per share. \par \par \uc2  In comparison, the PE ratio of the Hong Kong stock market is 16 and that of the Jakarta stock market is about 9. Furthermore, if US companies revise their accounting methods to follow stricter standards (such as expensing stock option compensations to corporate executives), the PE ratio of S&P 500 companies may indeed rise to exceed 45. Hence, the large fall of the US equity markets may actually be seen as "predictable market corrections" to more reasonable levels. \par \par \uc2  Now, in spite of the sharp fall in U.S. share prices, American households keep \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  because housing prices in the U.S. have not collapsed. This is because the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the Federal \b \highlight22\uc2 Reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  Board (the "Fed"), has aggressively cut \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , making mortgage financing for home purchases very cheap. \par \par \uc2  The result of the robust U.S. housing market is therefore not surprising: U.S. consumer demand is rising. Hence there is little doubt that the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery is fragile and the corporate accounting scandals have not helped. However, there is also little doubt that the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is likely to grow faster in 2002 than in 2001. \par \par \uc2  U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is expected to rise from 1.1 percent in 2001 to 2.5 percent (the U.S. government is predicting 3 percent to 3.5 percent) in 2002. Consequently, the world's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is also expected to rise from 2.5 percent in 2001 to 3 percent this year. \par \par \uc2  Hence the likelihood of the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  growing faster cannot be bad for Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  As far as international relations and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  are concerned, the benefits of the world events for Indonesia are more apparent. Take the U.S. foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  on Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  After Sept. 11, its foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  priority on Indonesia has shifted from human rights to the war on terrorism. Our support for the U.S. in this war has certainly helped smoothen the support given by the IMF and the international donor community to Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  After Sept. 11, U.S. support to Indonesia has indeed widened from financial assistance to military assistance, including what seems to be the gradual relaxation of the U.S. military embargo on Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Continual IMF assistance to Indonesia is important for two main reasons. Firstly, IMF's "seal of approval" on the Indonesian government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is necessary to help ensure financial support from the rest of the international donor community: the World Bank, Asian Development Bank, etc. Hence, the direct impact of IMF support is a budgetary impact. \par \par \uc2  The second reason why IMF support is necessary for us is that the "IMF \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  program" is seen as a "market benchmark" to judge whether the Indonesian government is doing the "right things". Market players' focus on the implementation of the IMF program, which determines relations between the IMF and Indonesia, should not be underestimated. \par \par \uc2  A \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  survey reveals that the rupiah exchange rate is determined mainly by two factors. One, the Indonesian political situation, and two, the government's relations with the IMF. Hence, if the political situation is stable and Indonesia's relations with the IMF are good, the rupiah is likely to be stable or likely to strengthen. \par \par \uc2  This perception is supported by evidence. Earlier this year, the sale of Bank Central Asia, which was part of the IMF program, greatly helped strengthen the rupiah from 10,400 at the end of last year, to 9,000 to the US dollar. \par \par \uc2  With an international environment that is becoming positive for Indonesia, why is our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  growing at only 3 percent to 4 percent a year compounded by an alarming decrease of foreign investment? \par \par \uc2  The answer is that we basically have six structural obstacles to rapid \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery: (1) political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; (2) a paralyzed banking sector; (3) a technically bankrupt corporate sector; (4) an ineffective legal system; (5) lack of confidence among Indonesia's own \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  elite; and (6) poor foreign investor confidence. \par \par \uc2  To remove these obstacles, Indonesia must introduce serious structural reforms, ranging from legal reforms to redefining regional autonomy. The tasks may take years, if not a whole generation, to complete. \par \par \uc2  However, these changes are absolutely crucial if Indonesia is to once again become a "haven" for foreign or domestic investors. \par \par \uc2  Therefore current world events may present an opportunity for us to speed up \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery as long as Indonesia does more to make herself attractive amid increasing global competition for investment capital. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020729dy7t000mo\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
