\par\par \b \uc2  Vague  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  vision causes business disarray. \b0\par\par\uc2 924 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 July 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  7 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Weakness in national leadership has had a more negative impact than positive impact, according to some economists. The Jakarta Post's contributor Rikza Abdullah talked to Djisman S. Simandjuntak, executive director of Prasetya Mulya business school, who shared his thoughts on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  vision of President Megawati Soekarnoputri's administration. \par \par \uc2  Question: Would you say the government lacks commitment to \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform? \par \par \uc2  Answer: The government apparently has no intention to make \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform and has no clear direction in its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies. The business community, therefore, cannot move forward and make accurate business plans. \par \par \uc2  Radical \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform and the redesigning of the basic architecture of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies are very important for the country to respond to radical changes in the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Globalization has made it possible for investors to move their funds - in the form of either portfolio or direct investments - from one country to another, drastically altering business competition. Former closed-market countries like China and those in Eastern Europe have now opened their markets. \par \par \uc2  So, we need open, market-driven \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies supported by the business community. \par \par \uc2  Q: Does this mean that Megawati's government has no clear vision in its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies? \par \par \uc2  A: Look what's happening in the privatization of state firms. Part of the privatization process has been hampered by protests by local authorities seeking democratization in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . If the government had a clear vision, it would have been able to find a legitimate form of privatization in line with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  democratization. \par \par \uc2  Q: What has caused this lack of vision? Is it because of Megawati's choice of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  advisers? \par \par \uc2  A: Her aides actually include senior consultants Ali Wardhana and Widjojo Nitisastro. They became great (several years ago) because they then worked under the strong leadership of former president Soeharto. If they now perform poorly, it is probably because they are working under the weak leadership of Megawati. \par \par \uc2  Her lack of leadership can be seen from the recent conflict among her ministers on Indonesia's cooperation with the International Monetary Fund. Another indication of her weak leadership is the prolonged legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused by very poor law enforcement. \par \par \uc2  Q: What are the good points of her leadership? \par \par \uc2  A: She has acted positively in the development of monetary affairs, banking and the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . She's been able to stabilize the rupiah's exchange rate. This is related to improvements in the balance of payments due to the return of capital to Indonesia, which flew out of the country during the crisis. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah's stability has helped curb inflation, even though the year-on-year inflation rate is still in double digits. \par \par \uc2  A positive development in banking has been the improvement in the health of banks' operations after the sale of part of their assets by the Indonesian Banking Restructuring Agency (IBRA). \par \par \uc2  As for the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Megawati's administration has been able to reduce its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  by reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Q: And the shortcomings? \par \par \uc2  A: The long list includes slow \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, high unemployment, the decline in exports and imports, weak investment promotion, the slow disposal of assets by the IBRA, slow privatization, the absence of progress in dealing with bad debtors and the eradication of corruption, poor law enforcement, the poor management of security and the lack of commitment to reforming policies. \par \par \uc2  Q: Could you elaborate? \par \par \uc2  A: Our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grew by 2.5 percent during the first half of this year, far lower than the annual 4 percent growth in 2000. The decline of exports and investment indicates that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is supported by domestic consumption. We cannot continually rely on this because so far we do not know where consumers get their money from. Most probably, the money is from the liquidation of their assets. \par \par \uc2  We need export-led \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth because we are in dire need of foreign exchange earnings to service external debts and to pay obligations related to foreign investments. True, the decline of exports was partly caused by the slowdown of the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but we would have been able to boost our exports if we had directed past investments to export-oriented industries, instead of projects destined for the local market. \par \par \uc2  The decline of imports (by 25.8 percent in the first quarter of this year and by about 5 percent in the second quarter, according to the latest quarterly report of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) also indicates the slowdown of investment activities, which traditionally rely mostly on imports of machinery and intermediate products. \par \par \uc2  The combination of the decline in investment and exports has affected \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and worsened unemployment. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, the absence of progress in the dealing of bad debtors and the eradication of corruption, poor law enforcement and management of security have created a bad perception of Indonesia's business and investment environment, particularly for foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  Q: What would improve the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ? \par \par \uc2  A: Because the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is very much affected by debt services, the government should reduce debts by repaying its debt principles. There are three options to obtain funds for their repayment. First, it could accelerate the privatization of state companies and the sales of assets currently held by IBRA. \par \par \uc2  Second, it could activate the secondary bond market, so the bonds for the restructuring of banks could be refinanced with the capital to be generated from the sales of new bonds at the time of their maturity. Third, the government should take bold measures to accelerate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, so that the government can increase revenue from \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020729dy7u000xt\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
