\par\par \b \uc2  Exports fall 6.73 percent in first semester. \b0\par\par\uc2 421 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 August 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The country's export performance weakened during the first half of this year due to weak global demand, the Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS) said on Thursday. \par \par \uc2  BPS said that exports fell 6.73 percent as of June to US$27.38 billion from $29.35 billion during the same period last year. \par \par \uc2  The bureau said that oil and gas exports dropped 19.05 percent, while non-oil and gas exports slowed by 2.73 percent to $21.74 billion from $22.36 billion. \par \par \uc2  BPS deputy chairman Slamet Mukeno said that the slow global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery had affected the country's exports. \par \par \uc2  Government trade officials had previously said that lingering labor conflicts and security problems at home would have a negative impact on the country's exports as these \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  had triggered foreign buyers to shift their orders to other countries in the region. \par \par \uc2  The decline in exports, coupled with falling foreign direct investments, resulted in modest \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth mainly driven by consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  But analysts have said that if exports and investments continued to fall, consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  would eventually weaken, thus putting a brake on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \par \par \uc2  However, although the country's exports have been negatively affected by the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown, they have recently started to pick up, thanks to signs of recovery in the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , one of Indonesia's major export markets. \par \par \uc2  A higher demand trend can be seen in export figures in June to the country's two largest export destinations, the U.S. and Japan, which rose sharply compared to the previous month. \par \par \uc2  Shipments to the U.S. totaled $802 million in June against $645.0 million in May and those to Japan rose to $589.2 million from $505.4 million. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, BPS said that total exports in June rose to $5.07 billion from $4.7 billion in May, while imports rose to $2.41 billion from $2.39 billion in May. \par \par \uc2  This brings the country's trade surplus to $2.66 billion this month, compared to $2.31 billion surplus in May. \par \par \uc2  A pick up in the U.S. and Japan, the world's two major \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  giants, should give enough power toward global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, which eventually will create higher import demand. \par \par \uc2  But economists warn that renewed concern over the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  may hurt export growth later in the year, following a string of financial scandals that has sent market confidence stumbling. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020802dy820000g\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
