\par\par \b \uc2  SATURDAY'S EDITORIALS FROM INDONESIAN DAILIES. \b0\par\par\uc2 633 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 August 2002\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 Asia Pulse Pte Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMY\b0 \highlight\uc2  WOBBLING \par \par \uc2  Declining inflation and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  seemed to be the only encouraging news in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  field that President Megawati Soekarnoputri could show off in her first annual progress report to the People's Consultative Assembly on Thursday as almost all other key indicators pointed to a bleaker outlook. \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in terms of gross domestic product, on annual basis, was only 2.15 percent in the first quarter, consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  is decreasing, exports were down 6.73 percent in the first six months, and investment remained depressed. President Megawati rightly cited the main causes of all these \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  woes: Legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  inconsistency. Despite this bleak, overall outlook, the situation is by no means hopeless, provided the three branches of government are united and determined in managing this critical condition with a high sense of urgency and the right set of priorities. The government has set an appropriate scale of priorities in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 , judicial and political reform. The only problem is haphazard execution not only due to problems within the executive branch but also because of the virtual absence of a sense of crisis within the judicial and \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  branches of the government. They should realize that the government, weighed down by more than US$135 billion of foreign and domestic debts or almost 100 percent as large as the gross domestic product, and debt service burdens already taking more than one third of its operating \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , cannot be expected to provide pumppriming for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The Assembly members who are convening their annual meeting should realize how critical the situation is now. - The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  LEADERS' POWER \par \par \uc2  Long before the annual session of the People's Consultative Assembly began, the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  gained the impression that deliberations on the fourth amendment to the Constitution would run smoothly. There was a guarantee to that effect from the leaders of the four major political parties, namely Megawati Soekarnoputri (PDIP), Akbar Tanjung (Golkar), Hamzah Haz (PPP) and Amien Rais (PAN). But in reality now things are developing in a different direction. On the first day of the MPR session, there were already strong indications that the deliberations will be contentious and be marked by many disturbances in the form not only of Assemblymen's interruptions but also of a movement to collect signatures to oppose proposed amendments to the Constitution. More than 200 Assembly members, mostly from the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDIP), were reported to have signed a statement rejecting the idea of altering the Constitution. In opposing the constitutional amendment process, the PDIP Assembly members were in fact challenging a decision of their party leader who is also president of this republic. The common understanding reached previously by the leaders of the four major parties is about to be disavowed by MPR members of the same parties. In adopting a stand contrary to what their own leaders had decided, these Assembly members claimed to be acting as real representative of the people. They forgot that what the people chose was their parties and not them personally, meaning they are in the Assembly as their parties' representatives. But now these Assembly members have ignored their own party leaders' decision. As such, it seems no bond exists any longer between leaders and followers. There is no more room for consensus nor for any common commitment. Only falseness is left. The party leaders built their agreement up in the sky, far from their base, far from earth. But, ironically, they feel that they have built something precious, down to earth. It seems the phenomenon of powerful leaders is about to disappear. Or perhaps it is already gone. What remains are straw leaders who are fragile, who resemble bean stalks that collapse when the wind blows. - Media Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020020805dy83000b6\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
