\par\par \b \uc2  Blaming only the IMF a deceitful gimmick. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,088 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 August 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  6 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Abdul Mongid, Alumni, University of Wales, United Kingdom \par \par \uc2  One main theme of discussion, especially among economists and politicians, is how to "get divorced" from the International Monetary Fund (IMF). The reason for this is: The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has not yet fully recovered since the 1998 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, even though Indonesia has been the IMF's patient. The second reason is the IMF's prescriptions, which have always placed added pressure on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Critics of the IMF use the bank restructuring \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a perfect example of how the IMF has tried to make Indonesia poorer. \par \par \uc2  The IMF has been active in formulating and applying almost all \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies since the 1998 crisis emerged - from the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Discussing the role of the IMF means reviewing the Letter of Intent (LoI) signed by both parties. Basically, the LoI contains the following items: \par \par \uc2  a. Monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 : At the core of the IMF's prescription on this issue is an effort to tighten monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , to curb inflation and resist depreciation of the rupiah. To make the monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  credible, the IMF has suggested that the government makes \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  independent. This is a clear attempt to build up confidence in the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  b. Financial sector reform: The IMF believes the real problem in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the fragile banking sector is corruption and the herd mentality, which is why it tends to support the liquidation of ailing banks. Liquidation will improve the structure of Indonesian banks and improve their efficiency. \par \par \uc2  To improve the capital position of the banking system, the IMF has suggested a recapitalization program. To improve governance, the IMF has also suggested a banking supervision master plan. The swift selling of shares owned by government is important to reduce the burden on the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The IMF has also suggested legal action against bankers and bank owners who have committed crimes. \par \par \uc2  c. Corporate and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  governance, transparency and accountability. The IMF knows the country's scale of corruption, collusion and nepotism in Indonesia and its implications. Based on a report by International Transparency, Indonesia is the most corrupt country in Asia and one of the worst in the world. \par \par \uc2  To make Indonesia sustainable, improving corporate and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  governance is essential. Blaming the private sector is not fair because the lack of governance arises from the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector. The rule of law does not work and proximity to political patrons is more important than good behavior. The exercising of a court decision is very costly and fraught with \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  d. \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 : The IMF suggests the government reduce external debt by reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially on goods such as oil. Rationalization of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  would provide a sustainable basis; \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  allowances would be reviewed to achieve the poorest. All non-budgetary funds should be managed under one escrow account. \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  management should be reviewed and necessary action should be taken to expand \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues. \par \par \uc2  e. Decentralization: The government must reconsider the impact of its decentralization \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and take actions to reduce it. Improving local \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  to increase sustainability and governance is also important. \par \par \uc2  f. \b \highlight22\uc2 Central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform: Granting \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's independence would provide credibility and a long-term perspective to monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Increasing corporate governance, transparency and accountability would create a sustainable basis. To achieve its targets, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  must review all its systems. \par \par \uc2  g. Macroeconomic framework: The main principle to achieve recovery under the IMF's guidance is prudential macroeconomic \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Lowering inflation, reducing the debt ratio from 100 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) to less than 65 percent of GDP and a maximum \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of 5 percent of GDP are all examples of prudential macroeconomic \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The IMF also requires BI to reduce the growth and quantity of base money to boost the exchange rate. \par \par \uc2  h. Others: The IMF also requires the government to improve the business climate by boosting the energy sector, improving agricultural \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and conserving natural resources to achieve long-term sustainability. Last, but not least, is the government's obligation to amend regulations on environmental issues and the management of natural resources. \par \par \uc2  The LoI should be considered as covenants in the credit market. Improving transparency and accountability has been \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  demand for some time. Long-term development perspectives are necessary amid the failure of previous governments to reduce widespread deforestation. Reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the rich and transferring it to the poor would help foster national unity. \par \par \uc2  The problems and failures of IMF-supported programs should be investigated with more realistic perspectives. Indonesia's indecisive attitude may play a more significant role in the failure of many of these programs. When the government in November 1997 closed 16 ailing banks, the market welcomed the news. Yet the situation worsened when people sensed foul play. \par \par \uc2  Many of us blame the IMF for the woes of the agricultural sector in Indonesia. The opening of grain markets has caused local products to be driven out of the market due to their high prices - for which we must blame our negotiators. The flood of imported grain may also have arisen because of Indonesia's inability to stop illegal imports and so guard the interests of farmers. The same failure also occurred in the case of sugar cane. \par \par \uc2  Suggesting that nationalized assets from ailing banks are sold swiftly is correct. The amount of money that has been poured into saving the banking system has almost reached Rp 700 trillion. Quick selling does incur large losses, but this is the cost of the crisis. Slow and inactive efforts to sales, plus corruption, have worsened the problem and there is a tendency for these ailing banks to take the government hostage. \par \par \uc2  The failure to achieve the results as expected in partnership with the IMF should be thought out calmly. The IMF's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  prescription, which has caused a downturn in the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  cannot be rejected. But blaming the IMF for the slow \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery and all its failures could create other problems. Experience teaches us that when we blame the IMF, the international community thinks we are diverting the issue away from making efforts to combat corruption, transparency and accountability. \par \par \uc2  We should be mature by blaming the failure on ourselves, not the IMF. After all, we have not yet applied all suggestions and prescriptions. The IMF is important for Indonesia and the other way around. Good cooperation may bring better results than if we continue to blame each other. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020809dy890000b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
