\par\par \b \uc2  Growth target in 2003  \highlight22\uc2 budget \highlight\uc2  seen as too optimistic. \b0\par\par\uc2 660 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 August 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Economists said the government was being too optimistic with its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target of 5 percent for next year, as stated in its 2003 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  draft, as they argued that the future course of the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  remained \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  In the draft, unveiled by President Megawati Soekarnoputri on Friday, the government hoped that gross domestic product (GDP) would grow by 5 percent, compared to an estimated 4 percent this year, on the back of expected improvement in exports and investments resulting from a strong global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  However, critics said they did not expect a quick recovery in the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  particularly because the major \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  powers, particularly the U.S. and Japan, were still struggling to recover from the current doldrums. \par \par \uc2  Achieving higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is crucial to helping resolve various problems in the country particularly the huge unemployment problem, which according to one estimate has reached more than 40 million and could potentially trigger widespread social unrest. \par \par \uc2  The 5 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target is also the basis for achieving other targets in the 2003 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  such as a higher \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue and lower \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Gadjah Mada University economist Sri Adingsih said even if the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  did grow stronger next year, Indonesia would not likely benefit from it, as various problems at home - such as a poor investment climate - had yet to be addressed. \par \par \uc2  "I am worried that investments and exports will not recover in 2003, as the government has not been serious in improving the business climate. \par \par \uc2  "There are also problems with exports, especially since we're facing tougher competition from other countries, mainly China," Sri told The Jakarta Post over the weekend. \par \par \uc2  An improved showing in exports and investment would be beneficial in pushing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, which has been relying heavily on strong domestic consumption for the past two years. \par \par \uc2  During the first semester of this year, exports fell by 6.73 percent to US$27.38 billion from the same period last year, while foreign direct investment (FDI) approvals dropped by at least 42 percent to $2.5 billion. \par \par \uc2  With the outlook remaining gloomy, Sri said the five percent growth was unrealistic. "My prediction for next year is that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will only grow by 4 percent." \par \par \uc2  University of Indonesia economist M. Chatib Basri said although exports could be higher next year, it would not be significant enough to push \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth to reach the 5 percent level. \par \par \uc2  "Exports only contribute 20 percent to (\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) growth," he said, adding that next year's growth would still largely depend on domestic consumption. \par \par \uc2  Anton Gunawan, an economist at Citibank, was also of the opinion that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth next year would be less than 5 percent. \par \par \uc2  "I think achieving 5 percent growth would be rather hard. A 4.5 percent growth would be my most optimistic prediction under the current circumstances," Anton told the Post. \par \par \uc2  Other macro \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  assumptions in the 2003 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  draft are: a rupiah exchange rate of Rp 8,700 per U.S. dollar, an inflation rate of 8 percent and \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  (SBI) of 13 percent. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, the International Monetary Fund praised the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  draft. \par \par \uc2  "It's a sound \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  which should help reinforce macroeconomic stability," David Nellor, IMF's representatives in the country, was quoted by Dow Jones as saying, adding that efforts to reduce fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  to rein in the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  were encouraging. \par \par \uc2  "It shows a lot of effort to bring about a more stable \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  environment," he added. \par \par \uc2  The government is targeting a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of 1.3 percent of GDP next year. \par \par \uc2  To achieve the target, the government has proposed a cut in expensive \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  on fuel, electricity and others by 39 percent to Rp 25.3 trillion. \par \par \uc2  The government is also planning to increase \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collection by 18.7 percent to Rp 260.8 trillion. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020819dy8j000ha\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
