\par\par \b \uc2  ILO defends RI workers amid investment outflows. \b0\par\par\uc2 656 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 August 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Moch. N. Kurniawan, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The International Labor Organization (ILO) came to the defense of Indonesian workers on Friday, saying that unproductive laborers should not be considered as the only factor hindering the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  here. \par \par \uc2  "I doubt that the labor issue is the major problem causing investors to flee from here. What I see is Indonesia is on the right track as all parties are trying to improve the labor system," ILO director for Indonesia Alan Boulton told the Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2  Admitting that the country's workers had to improve productivity, Boulton stressed that political and legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  as well as rampant corruption were the major problems that had caused many companies to relocate elsewhere. \par \par \uc2  The Korean Chamber of Commerce warned the government on Thursday that South Korean firms would pull out of Indonesia if it failed to address various labor problems ranging from unfavorable labor \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , soaring increase of wage, poor productivity and constant strikes. \par \par \uc2  Recently, U.S. footwear manufacturers Nike and Reebok cut back their operations in the country, citing increasing labor problems. \par \par \uc2  Some foreign and domestic firms have also criticized two new labor bills currently being deliberated in the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR), saying that they were too pro-worker and hurt their businesses. \par \par \uc2  Minister of Manpower and Transmigration Jacob Nuwa Wea said this week that the government would revise some 35 chapters of the bills which have been widely rejected by the country's workers. \par \par \uc2  Boulton hailed recent meetings between labor unions and the Ministry of Manpower and Transmigration, as well as the business community and the ministry as part of efforts to create good labor laws. \par \par \uc2  However, Indonesia had to concern itself with its workers' low productivity which has eroded its competitiveness, he added. \par \par \uc2  "Workers here must improve their productivity to compete with workers in other countries," he said. \par \par \uc2  According to the World Bank, there are increasing signs since early 1990s that Indonesia's competitiveness is being eroded by several factors: rising labor costs, low worker productivity and increasing industrial unrest. \par \par \uc2  Minister of Manpower and Transmigration Jacob Nuwa Wea said earlier that an average Indonesian worker produced six times less than an average Malaysian and eight times less than an average Japanese worker. \par \par \uc2  Boulton supported the current debates over labor bills however, which were focused on recognizing labor rights, not allowing military intervention in industrial disputes and regional administrations' power on addressing manpower issues. \par \par \uc2  The bills guarantee workers freedom to choose his or her worker union, a right that workers did not posses in the previous law. Workers would also have the right to negotiate with employers on working terms and conditions, while in the past employers were totally in control of the workers. \par \par \uc2  There would also be a guarantee in the system that no military intervention in resolving disputes between workers and employers, which was dominant in the past. \par \par \uc2  The authority of regional administrations to deal with local manpower problems would be legalized under the proposed law. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, senior executive at the Indonesian Workers Union (SPSI) Arif Sujito warned the government to meet its promise to revise 35 chapters of the labor bills. \par \par \uc2  According to him, three crucial issues: the approval from the Industrial Relations Settlement Court (PPHI) on worker dismissal, criminal action and a code of conduct for strikes, are among articles that have to be revised. \par \par \uc2  Arif said on dismissal matters, approval from PPHI was important to prevent employers from arbitrarily dismissing workers. \par \par \uc2  Regarding criminal action, he said, wrongdoing such as cheating, or theft should be categorized as a major fault, therefore those who carry out such practices would be only punished by dismissal. \par \par \uc2  At present, those wrongdoings are considered a crime, which can be tried in the criminal court. \par \par \uc2  On strikes, the new bills may stipulate that the employer must pay workers who go on strike but follow the proper procedures, Arif said. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020824dy8o0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
