\par\par \b \uc2  PDI Perjuangan wants simultaneous elections in 2004. \b0\par\par\uc2 665 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 August 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Fabiola Desy Unidjaja and Muhammad Nafik, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  President Megawati Soekarnoputri's Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI Perjuangan) has backed calls for both presidential and \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  elections to take place at the same time in 2004, citing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and socio-political reasons. \par \par \uc2  "For now, we still believe that it would be more appropriate to hold simultaneous elections for the presidency and the legislature," PDI Perjuangan secretary-general Soetjipto quoted Megawati as saying. \par \par \uc2  Speaking to journalists after a weekly meeting at the party's head office in South Jakarta on Tuesday, Soetjipto argued that it would be more efficient to hold the elections concurrently. \par \par \uc2  He added that simultaneous elections for the presidency and legislature would curb possible outbreaks of social and political tension or clashes between supporters of rival political groups, which had been frequent in the past. \par \par \uc2  Megawati's views contradicts those of the leaders of other political parties, who insist on maintaining the old practice of separating the presidential election from the poll for the legislature. \par \par \uc2  According to Soetjipto, Megawati told the meeting that the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  and popular emotions should be taken into account in deciding on the best arrangements for elections. \par \par \uc2  "Two separate elections mean more money and the time gap will end up producing a prolonged period of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Soetjipto said. \par \par \uc2  He warned that election campaigns had always affected the country's political stability and that the PDI Perjuangan could not imagine the risks involved in organizing separate presidential and \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  elections. \par \par \uc2  However, he said that the nation's biggest party would not rule out the possibility of changing its stance on the holding of both elections. \par \par \uc2  "We can still change our stance if we deem it more advantageous to hold the two elections separately," Soetjipto remarked. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debate has surfaced on whether it will be efficient and effective to hold the presidential and \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  elections separately or simultaneously. \par \par \uc2  The General Elections Commission (KPU) has set the date for the general election to elect a new legislature for June 2004, but has refrained from setting a date for the direct presidential election. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the government are currently deliberating the political bills, during which process the date of the election will be decided upon. \par \par \uc2  However, deputy KPU chairman Ramlan Surbakti suggested on Tuesday that the presidential and \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  elections be held separately in order to ensure their quality. \par \par \uc2  "The presidential and \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  elections should not be held simultaneously as this would undermine the quality of both polls," he said. \par \par \uc2  "If the elections are held at the same time, many political issues will run out of control and this will make the elections defective," Surbakti added. \par \par \uc2  Bambang Widjojanto, a senior activist from the Partnership for Governance Reform in Indonesia, said that even if the presidential and \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  elections were to be held at different times, they should still both be held in 2004. \par \par \uc2  Electoral timetables outlined by KPU \par \par \uc2  November 2002 - April 2003: Registration and verification of political parties contesting general elections. \par \par \uc2  June 2003: Decision on eligible parties contesting elections. \par \par \uc2  July 2003: Deadline for voter registration and announcement of number of contested seats for local councils. \par \par \uc2  August 2003: Nomination of local and central legislators by parties and members of regional representatives council (DPD) by individuals. \par \par \uc2  September-October 2003: \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  responses to list of names of \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  candidates. \par \par \uc2  November 2003: Announcement of permanent lists of local and national legislators, and DPD members. \par \par \uc2  December 2003: Nomination of presidential and vice presidential candidates by political parties. \par \par \uc2  January 2004: Announcement of permanent list of voters. \par \par \uc2  February 2004: \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  responses to presidential and vice presidential candidates. \par \par \uc2  March 2004: Announcement of eligible presidential and vice presidential candidates. \par \par \uc2  April-May 2004: Election campaigns by political parties. \par \par \uc2  June 2004: Voters go to the polls and announcement of election winners \par \par \uc2  July 2004: Announcement of elected \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  candidates. \par \par \uc2  Date of direct presidential election depends on deliberation of political bills in the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020828dy8s00001\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
