\par\par \b \uc2  Future challenges to Indonesia-Singapore ties. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,193 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 August 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  6 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Jusuf Wanandi, Founder, Member Board of Trustees, Centre for Strategic and International Studies, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  A bilateral Indonesia-Singapore Conference was held in mid-July in Jakarta for two full days. The idea to reestablish the bilateral conferences between the two countries, after a hiatus of over 15 years, was based on the fact that changes in both countries have been deep and immense, and that new challenges have arisen in the region. \par \par \uc2  Those factors have made it imperative to lay down a much broader based relationship than before. For instance, under president Soeharto, the relationship was based on an excellent understanding between two persons, namely Soeharto and Lee Kuan Yew. \par \par \uc2  Now there are many other actors in the bilateral relationship: The parliament, the private sector, the non government organizations, the press, intellectuals, and even \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  opinion. This is especially true for Indonesia, and will also be valid for Singapore, although for some time to come the Singapore government will still play a dominant role in this relationship. However, the Singapore government alone could no more handle it by itself, because on the Indonesian side so many actors have emerged and the Indonesian government no longer have the monopoly in the conduct of diplomacy. \par \par \uc2  One of the new major challenges facing the world and the region is globalization and its dramatic impact on every country and society. In addition, there is the new threat of global terrorism that might change the strategic environment for the region. Both these changes have made cooperation between the two countries an imperative, because bilateral and regional cooperation will make it easier for both to overcome them. \par \par \uc2  But at the same time, perceptions about each other are still influenced by stereotypes and cliches, which have yet to be overcome. Indonesia sees Singapore as having a kiasu (self-centered and self-interested) mentality, mixed with some arrogance towards Indonesia. Singapore views Indonesia as a messy place that cannot gets its act together after five years of crisis. Therefore it sometimes looks down on Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  There are still a number of irritating problems for the Indonesians that have been subdued during the authoritarian rule of Soeharto. One is on the bilateral trade statistics that Singapore refuses to publish and provides them only to the government. Due to differences in the method of reporting, it is feared that the discrepancy could create misunderstanding. However, it should not be difficult to reconcile these differences. \par \par \uc2  Second, is the unfinished business of concluding an extradition treaty due to differences of interpretation of what constitutes "\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  criminality". Third, is the problem that has arisen because some maritime boundaries between the two have not been drawn. \par \par \uc2  Because of land reclamation in Singapore further \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  could be created on these boundaries. Former Foreign Minister Ali Alatas expressed it well, when he said that those irritants should be overcome for otherwise they might hamper future relations and cooperation. \par \par \uc2  Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew statements on Indonesia's policies, especially on terrorism and Islam in Indonesia were discussed. There were criticisms that they amounted to intervention in Indonesian domestic affairs, but also as having a negative influence on the international community's assessment about Indonesia's stability and her seriousness about dealing with terrorism. \par \par \uc2  It has been explained to the Indonesians in the Conference how damaging acts of terrorism, such as was planned by Jamaah Islamiyah last December in Singapore, could be for the credibility and stability of Singapore as an global communication hub and financial center. \par \par \uc2  That was the reason why SM Lee has been so strong in his reactions. It was also recognized by both sides that SM Lee has always and in many fora defended Indonesia's interests. \par \par \uc2  Other important issues have also been discussed. One positive outcome was the recognition of the need to find a new paradigm for the relationship in the future. It is no more true that Indonesia, big and populous, could be in the driver's seat on everything in bilateral and regional affairs, because in the meantime Singapore has developed into an important global communication and financial hub. \par \par \uc2  And so she has become important for Indonesia and can act as an "interlocutor" to the international community. Singapore also can assist and support in the development of some regions of Indonesia, as has been shown in the case of Batam and Bintan. \par \par \uc2  Indeed, most positive comments have come from the private sector. In the July talks reference was made about the participation of Singapore's private sector in Bintan and Batam, cooperation with Singtel, that has invested US$1 billion into Indonesia and in high technology. \par \par \uc2  It was an eye opener for the Indonesian side to be informed that in the meantime Singapore has become the third largest foreign investor in Indonesia, only after the U.S. and Japan, with over $20 billion worth of investments. \par \par \uc2  In the case of the Riau Islands (Batam and Bintan), the suggestion of the U.S. Trade Representative, Robert Zoellick, to include them as part of the bilateral FTA between the US and Singapore, has been explained. The proposal is well worth for the Indonesian government and the private sector to study and consider seriously. \par \par \uc2  Another subject that was an eye opener for Singaporeans has been the explanation on Islam in Indonesia. Five Muslim scholars and leaders have given an in depth explanation on the developments of Islam in Indonesia and the challenges it has been facing since Soeharto's demise. They very ably explained why radical and extremist Muslim groups are a minority and that there is no real danger that they will take over Islam's leadership in the future. \par \par \uc2  Those evaluations were not merely an intellectual discourse, but has been proven when the last annual session of the People's Consultative Assembly in August 2002 rejected with an overwhelming majority proposals to make the sharia into positive law, and to be included into the new Constitution. \par \par \uc2  This time the debate was not between Muslims and non-Muslims or nominal Muslims as have happened many times earlier but amongst Muslim scholars, ulema, intellectuals, politicians, and social leaders (including Nahdlatul Ulama and Muhammadiyah, two largest Muslim organizations). \par \par \uc2  Discussions on the new global and regional strategy after Sept. 11, the role of the U.S. in the region, as well as ASEAN's role, have been useful, but have not resulted in new ideas. It is a worthwhile topic to be taken up in the future. \par \par \uc2  Last but not least, it has been recognized and lauded that Singapore has made great efforts to assist Indonesia in education and health, in training the bureaucracy, educating young intellectuals in Singapore's excellent universities, and sending groups of doctors with medicine and equipments to help minus regions, including the Riau Islands. \par \par \uc2  This should be multiplied. It also can help project the concerns of a new Singapore for its needy neighbors, as she has already been doing for Cambodia and Myanmar. \par \par \uc2  In the end, both sides have agreed on the need for more bilateral dialogs and exchanges, also among members of parliament, business, the media, and the civil society. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020828dy8t0005z\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
