\par\par \b \uc2  Corruption a barrier to achieving  \highlight22\uc2 tax \highlight\uc2  revenue target. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,143 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 August 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The government, under its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  plan recently proposed to the legislature aims to increase its total \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and excise revenue by 18.7 percent to Rp 260.78 trillion (nearly US$30 billion) next year from Rp 219.62 trillion expected this year. Muhammad Chatib Basri, associate director of the University of Indonesia's Institute for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Social Research (LPEM), talked to The Jakarta Post contributor Rikza Abdullah. \par \par \uc2  Question: Is the government's target of increasing its revenue from \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and excise by 18.7 percent next year realistic? \par \par \uc2  Answer: The targeted revenue of Rp 260.78 trillion for 2003 is still too low because it will amount to only 13.3 percent of the country's gross domestic product (GDP) (projected to reach Rp 1,955.47 trillion that year). This will indicate a slight increase from this year's target of Rp 219.62 trillion, which will be 13 percent of the GDP (projected at Rp 1,685.38 trillion). In other countries \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collection can exceed 15 percent of their GDPs. \par \par \uc2  But the 2003 target would be very difficult to achieve if the government doesn't intensify \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collection and improve its \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  administration. The current poor \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collection has made it easy for companies and people to avoid \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  payment, while the poor \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  administration has made it possible for \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials and taxpayers to collaborate in corruption. \par \par \uc2  Q: Which is the larger amount, the amount of money siphoned off by \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials or the amount that should have been paid by \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  evaders? \par \par \uc2  A: Maybe it's the amount of money siphoned off by \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials. But that will surely depend on each case. A taxpayer, who does not want to pay an income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp 600 million, would prefer to pay Rp 150 million (as a bribe) to \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials so he could pay only Rp 50 million for the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Q: So how can the government expect a 5 percent growth by 2003? \par \par \uc2  A: That expectation does not make sense to me. But my consideration is not related to the planned increase in \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collection and reduction of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  because the impact of energy (fuel and electricity) price increases is not substantial and the planned increase in \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collection is not significant. \par \par \uc2  Because the country's GDP grew by 3.3 percent in 2001, when the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was slowing down, it is reasonable if we expect the GDP to grow by 3.8 percent this year due to improvement in the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  But it would be unrealistic if we project the GDP to expand drastically to reach 5 percent in 2003 with no improvement in investment. Domestic investment will not increase significantly that year because banks are still reluctant to channel credits to companies, while foreign investors are scared to enter Indonesia due to social and labor unrest as well as business \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Q: How far will the GDP grow? \par \par \uc2  A: Based on the optimistic scenario by the LPEM, the GDP is likely to grow by 4.4 percent in 2003. \par \par \uc2  Q: Is it realistic for the government to increase its revenue from income \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on non-oil sectors by 27 percent for 2002? \par \par \uc2  A: It would be too hard. Its success will depend mostly on whether the government can identify and force \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  evaders to pay their income \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and all \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials to pass on all income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  payments to the state treasury. Corruption related to the collection of income \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  is relatively easier and larger in the amount of money involved than that related to value added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Many business people, therefore, complain on corruption related to income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Some executives of the 1,700 companies surveyed by the LPEM recently said they would rather allow the government to impose an extra \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  of some 7 percent to 8 percent on their incomes than to pay bribes, which can reach 10 percent of their incomes, to corrupt \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials. \par \par \uc2  Q: How can the government expect its revenue from value added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (VAT) to increase by 17.1 percent to Rp 82 trillion in 2003? \par \par \uc2  A: This target is easy to achieve because domestic consumption is likely to continue growing at an annual rate of 6 percent and, therefore, will remain strong. The planned reduction of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not boost inflation because the country's inflation is influenced more by the fluctuations of the rupiah's value than the movements of fuel prices. \par \par \uc2  Recent experience indicates that the inflation rate was on a downward trend in the months following fuel price increases in January, because the rupiah's value appreciated against the U.S. dollar. \par \par \uc2  Q: Will the smuggling of manufactured goods into the country affect the VAT revenue target? \par \par \uc2  A: The smuggling of manufactured goods will affect domestic producers, who have to pay \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , in competing against such untaxed imported products. But it is unlikely to cause VAT collection to fall short of the target. \par \par \uc2  The targeted revenue of Rp 82 trillion, which would be equal to about 4.2 percent of the country's GDP, is still too low. The government's VAT revenue should actually be able to reach 8 percent of the country's GDP (projected at Rp 1,955.47 trillion). \par \par \uc2  Q: Will the government face difficulties in raising its revenue from excise on cigarettes to Rp 27.64 trillion in 2003? \par \par \uc2  A: Yes, it will. Even though smokers have a difficult time quitting, their cigarette consumption will decrease when cigarette prices increase. The sales of cigarettes during the first seven months of this year declined due to an increase in price. \par \par \uc2  Q: How about the government's expectation to increase revenue from import duties to Rp 13.82 trillion from Rp 12.25 trillion, while the country will enter a free trade era in 2003 under the ASEAN Free Trade Agreement (AFTA)? \par \par \uc2  A: The government will be able to achieve its expectation because it's expanding the number of commodities subject to import duties, including agricultural produce. However, such a trend contradicts the principles of AFTA and the World Trade Organization (WTO). \par \par \uc2  Perhaps, the expansion on imposition of duties would not violate the AFTA and WTO principles if the rates are still within the allowable range or the affected commodities are excluded from agreements; but the government's inconsistency in trade liberalization should become our concern because it is a setback and may affect domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities. \par \par \uc2  Q: Will the government's plan to raise revenue from property \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  increase burdens on taxpayers? \par \par \uc2  A: It won't if the government pursues its target merely by intensifying \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collection. Many have evaded the payment of \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on land and buildings. The target will burden taxpayers if the government raises the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020829dy8t00002\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
