\par\par \b \uc2  Rupiah slides to 9,000 on weaker yen, Iraq. \b0\par\par\uc2 509 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 September 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  said it might sell off U.S. dollars in the currency market as the rupiah dropped on Monday to Rp 9,000 to the greenback, due to what the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  said was a weaker yen and the possible U.S. strike on Iraq. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah receded to its lowest level in nearly six weeks, ending the day at Rp 9,065 to the dollar from Rp 8,965. \par \par \uc2  "The problem with the rupiah is more regional. There are no other factors but regional ones," \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Deputy Governor Miranda Goeltom said prior to a hearing with the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  Commission IX for financial affairs. \par \par \uc2  "In maintaining monetary stability, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  sees it necessary and important to continue intervening in the foreign exchange market," she later told Antara. \par \par \uc2  She said \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  amid talks of war in the Middle East were weighing on the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  A possible U.S. strike on Iraq has put a strain on world markets while threatening to delay new investments across the globe. \par \par \uc2  "We're looking at this (Iraq) and seeing how it affects investment decisions, the stock markets and U.S. investors worldwide," Miranda said. \par \par \uc2  Dealers have also attributed the rupiah's fall on Monday to regional sentiment, as currencies from export-oriented countries, like South Korea and Singapore, tracked the yen's slide. \par \par \uc2  At Y122.25 to the dollar, the yen hit its lowest level in three months during Friday trading in New York. \par \par \uc2  Japan's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slump will benefit from a weaker yen, as lower prices, in terms of U.S. dollars, for its export products spell higher sales. \par \par \uc2  "I don't see any bad fundamentals at home," said analyst Khalil Rowter of PT Nusantara Capital. "The rupiah's fall is temporary." \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's ongoing reforms have earned it foreign loan commitments from creditors, such as the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) - deals that mean a supply for the dollar-starving market. \par \par \uc2  "It's quite possible that companies were stocking up on dollars to pay off foreign debts," Khalil said. \par \par \uc2  But he added that amid the absence of fresh leads, market players might have taken cues from regional issues and the local stock market, which has come under pressure lately. \par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) has been losing ground over the past three weeks, ending Monday at 420.21 from 421 points. Analysts have warned that the JSX main index could further recede should world stock markets continue to fall because of a possible U.S. strike against Iraq. \par \par \uc2  Khalil said the rupiah should actually benefit from war talks in the Middle East - the vault of the world's oil supply. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the oil supply normally props up prices, but Khalil said concerns over the U.S. and Japan's economies, the world's largest, had offset this fear. "If their economies weaken, demand for oil will drop as well." \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020917dy9h000bq\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
