\par\par \b \uc2  ADB revises upward RI's 2002 GDP growth estimate. \b0\par\par\uc2 493 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 September 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  A'an Suryana, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The Asian Development Bank (ADB) has revised upward its 2002 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth prediction for Indonesia from an earlier 3 percent to 3.2 percent. \par \par \uc2  The higher prediction was based on an expected recovery in exports, particularly on the back of higher oil prices. \par \par \uc2  The ADB said that consumption demand would be sustained, although at a lower rate than in 2001, and the agricultural sector would also perform well during the rest of this year. \par \par \uc2  The bank said in the "Asian Development Outlook 2002 Update" report that gross domestic product (GDP) growth for 2003 was projected at 4.4 percent. \par \par \uc2  ADB did not give its prediction for the oil price, but the optimistic projection seems possible amid the growing tension in the Middle East. \par \par \uc2  Due to fears of a U.S.-led attack on Iraq, oil hit US$30 a barrel for the first time in 18 months in August. \par \par \uc2  The higher oil price would benefit oil exporting countries like Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  With the increasing price of oil, Indonesian exports from the oil sector could increase as well, which could ease pressure on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The government has targeted the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow by 4 percent this year, and by about 5 percent next year. This year's growth is expected to be mainly driven by strong domestic consumption, while a stronger export performance next year is expected to help push \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth higher. \par \par \uc2  The higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth 