\par\par \b \uc2  RI answers WB's call for institutional reform. \b0\par\par\uc2 622 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 September 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Berni K. Moestafa, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The World Bank puts institution building at the heart of sustainable development in a report signaling the possibilities Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program presents for building better institutions, and the risk if the country fails to seize the opportunity. \par \par \uc2  Sustainable development hopes to align global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth on one side, with the decline in world's assets and the growing population on the other. \par \par \uc2  "Development is sustainable if the rules of the games are transparent and the game is inclusive," said the opening sentence of a recent report by the bank titled the World Development Report 2003. \par \par \uc2  The world's assets - be they physical, financial, human, social, or environmental - are limited and thus need better management of their portfolio, the report said. \par \par \uc2  It said that assets overexploitation and shortfalls could be resolved by improving markets and the institutions behind them. \par \par \uc2  "Many appropriate policies are known, but not implemented because of distribution issues and institutional weaknesses," it said. "Competent institutions pick up signals, balance interests, and execute agreed-on decisions." \par \par \uc2  Such institutions may be state owned, private or independent. To increase their competence, the report added, the poor and disenfranchised should be given access to decision making. \par \par \uc2  The message comes at a time when Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program demands sweeping changes on how institutions here run this country. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms have began since before the demise of Soeharto's authoritarian regime in 1998. \par \par \uc2  His fall led to a more aggressive take on Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  malaise and the transition into a democracy. This has opened up the opportunity to reshape the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  with greater \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  participation. "When more people are heard, fewer assets are wasted," the World Bank report said. \par \par \uc2  Led by the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Indonesia's reform program aims to purge market inefficiencies and instill macroeconomic stability. \par \par \uc2  Although not tied to sustainable development goals and often criticized as even contradicting them, the IMF program also deals with institutional reform issues. \par \par \uc2  For instance, corruption is undermining the effectiveness of foreign loans that international agencies like the IMF or World Bank provide. Part of these loans are being used to fund projects related to sustainable development. \par \par \uc2  The IMF program, also known as the Letter of Intent (LoI), calls for an anticorruption committee, transparency in state asset sales and improvements in the country's judiciary. \par \par \uc2  Such structural reform programs are more the work of the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank (ADB). Still, their programs depend on progress with the LoI which the IMF leads. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia as the fourth most populous nation in the world, has much to gain from molding its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  into a more sustainable pattern. \par \par \uc2  Despite ongoing steps toward reform, environmental and social conditions have worsened. \par \par \uc2  Soeharto's downfall teared down institutional control over the market and other social aspects. Yet the resulting power vacuum also led to legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Illegal logging, mining and fishing are worse than ever. \par \par \uc2  Widespread corruption within the country's judiciary undermines efforts to fight these illegal businesses and reduces foreign and domestic investor confidence in the country. \par \par \uc2  Analysts have said the pace with which the institutions were reforming is too slow to arrest the environmental decline. \par \par \uc2  So far foreign creditors and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  pressure through the media have been the biggest driving force behind reform. \par \par \uc2  Non-governmental organizations have decried the lack of a political leadership from both the government and the legislature. \par \par \uc2  " ... a leader who takes steps to build stronger institutions would reap benefits from the stronger \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the better environment only in the long run," said the report, adding: "this requires a stable setting with broad political support." \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020930dy9u0000e\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
