\par\par \b \uc2  Bali attack puts fragile  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2  at risk. \b0\par\par\uc2 612 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 October 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Berni K. Moestafa, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Economists feared an overall weakening of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  following the deadliest terrorist strike this country has ever seen. \par \par \uc2  They warned of bearish markets in a reaction that could stoke inflation and capital flight as the country braced for new instability. \par \par \uc2  Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Dorodjatun Kuntjoro-Jakti would meet businessmen Monday to brief them about the government's planned response to the apparent terror, said a press statement by Dorodjatun's office. \par \par \uc2  Saturday's bombings killed at least 182 people in a crowded tourist area of Bali. The popular island was long viewed as a safe heaven, exempt from the numerous armed conflicts across the country, including bomb blasts and unruly protests in Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  "The first reaction will be a run on the U.S. dollar," said Bank Mandiri chief economist Martin Panggabean on Sunday. \par \par \uc2  A steep fall in the rupiah would add to inflationary pressures and might prompt \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  to raise its benchmark rates. "If it (the rupiah) starts to drive \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  up then there is a risk to the overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Martin said. \par \par \uc2  The explosion has stirred new concern over Indonesia's fragile crawl up from the impacts of the 1997 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  Investment continues to fall but the rupiah's relative stability this year has driven \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's rates down and made bank loans more affordable. A jump in the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's rates would choke off lending and raise interest payments on government and private debts, pulling money away from much needed investments to drive the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "I think the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  will stop cutting its rates for the moment and might even start raising them again," Martin said. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah has been hovering at around 9,000 to the dollar over the past few weeks. Yet the stock market has already been under selling pressure since September, led by a downturn in Wall Street. Last week the Jakarta Stock Exchange Composite index lost a hefty 7 percent to end trading at 376.46. \par \par \uc2  Analysts commenting on the blast in Bali now predicted panic selling on the money and stock market when trading opens Monday. \par \par \uc2  According to Martin, the damage to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  however would be manageable if the rupiah fell to no further than 9,500. \par \par \uc2  University of Gadjah Mada economist Sri Adiningsih said the investment climate would take a big hit. "We might see weaker exports and foreign direct investment." \par \par \uc2  Overseas buyers could cancel orders from Indonesia and place new ones elsewhere, she added. \par \par \uc2  "How bad the impact will be on our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  depends on how effectively the government deals with the terrorism threat," she said. \par \par \uc2  Martin, however, said that cracking down on suspected terrorists would do little to halt the loss of capital. \par \par \uc2  "Capital is pouring out of Indonesia, with or without terrorists here, it has been this way for the past five years," he said, citing corruption and legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the main reasons why investors had been leaving the country in droves since 1997. \par \par \uc2  Chairman of the National \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Recovery Committee Sofyan Wanandi warned the government that the Bali terrorist strike could squash what little was left of investor confidence here. \par \par \uc2  "I am to meet 300 Singaporean businessmen tomorrow (Monday) who are mulling investments here, and on Wednesday a Swedish business delegation," said an emotional Sofyan. "What am I going to tell them?" \par \par \uc2  He said several local and foreign businessmen called him up, and "the foreigners talked about leaving, and the local investors said they would not make any new investments with security like this... this is bad," Sofyan mumbled. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020021014dyae0000h\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
