\par\par \b \uc2  Foreign businesses ask for review of customs law. \b0\par\par\uc2 572 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 October 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Rendi A. Witular, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Foreign business groups have said a revised customs law is a necessary part of the government's efforts to reform the country's customs service. \par \par \uc2  Speaking on behalf of the business groups, Phil Bell, a technical adviser for consultancy firm PriceWaterhouseCoopers (PWC), said the customs law should be revised to enhance accountability within the country's customs service and reduce the opportunity for corruption. \par \par \uc2  "Customs modernization and reform is used as the platform to achieve structural changes and efficiencies in the whole import and export process, and deliver significant \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  benefits," said Bell. \par \par \uc2  PWC is a member of the Customs Advisory Committee set up by the finance ministry with the main task of developing, evaluating and supervising customs \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and administration. PWC was included on the committee to represent the International Business Chamber of Indonesia, which groups all foreign business chambers in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  The establishment of the advisory committee was part of the government's ongoing efforts to reform the country's customs service, which is notoriously riddled with corruption. \par \par \uc2  There are at least seven articles in Law No. 10/1995 on customs that require revision, Bell said in a e-mail to The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2  One of them is Article 16, which regulates tariffs and import \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Bell said there was no simple and clear mechanism in the article for importers to report honest errors in underpaying import duties and to settle the payment. \par \par \uc2  At present, in case of underpayment the customs office will audit the company in question to confirm the underpaid amounts and then issue an underpayment notice. In some cases, the office imposes penalties. \par \par \uc2  The good reputation of an importer can be tarnished once it receives the underpayment receipt, as customs personnel will make of record of the error, which can deny a company the opportunity to receive special facilities in the future. \par \par \uc2  "There are therefore no incentives to a company reporting and settling honest mistakes," said Bell. \par \par \uc2  Several importers said that due to the complex bureaucratic process of settling underpayments, many companies would rather pay kickbacks to customs personnel than try to settle the matter legally. \par \par \uc2  Bell added that Article 16 also caused \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  for importers as it states that the customs office can provide a \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  classification ruling before or after goods are imported, but can only provide a valuation ruling after goods have been imported. \par \par \uc2  "Customs valuation is a complex issue, and the inability to gain a valuation ruling prior to entering into binding contractual arrangements does not provide a company with certainty," said Bell. \par \par \uc2  He also recommended for revision Article 93 and part three of Chapter VI of the customs law, which includes articles 30 to 35. \par \par \uc2  Article 93 deals with the formalities for lodging an objection to a customs assessment in relation to \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  classification and valuation. \par \par \uc2  Part three of Chapter VI of the law deals with customs declarations and liabilities for import duties. \par \par \uc2  When asked to comment on these suggestions, the head of the Customs and Excise Division at the Directorate General of Customs and Excise, Agus Sudarmadi, said thus far the directorate general saw no reason to review the customs law. \par \par \uc2  "We shall not recommend the revision of the customs law to the Ministry of Finance as the law can still adequately accommodate the interests of all customs stakeholders," Agus said. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020021021dyal000h0\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  IMF - Bali tragedy hurt  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2  in 2003. \b0\par\par\uc2 372 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 October 2002\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The International Monetary Fund (IMF) forecasted that the Bali bombing would slow the national and regional \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2003 since security problem has no longer been in regional issue but has become a global issue. Indonesia would suffer a lot from the increasing risk, which arises negative perception on investors. \par \par \uc2  "The impact is of course sensitive, depend on the security condition and Indonesian government response on the tragedy," he said in Singapore last week when explaining World \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Outlook. \par \par \uc2  Rogoff did not mention in detail on how great the impact would be but IMF estimated that Indonesian this year and next year \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth would stand at 3.5% and 4.5% respectively. Meanwhile government targeted 4% and 5% growth for the period. \par \par \uc2  He further explained that the increasing risk would burden investors with increasing cost such as insurance premium, and security cost. \par \par \uc2  "With indirect costs arising, investors risk perception would increase." \par \par \uc2  However he admitted that it was difficult to exactly predict the impact of global terrorism on Indonesia and regional \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. But for Indonesia, it would surely be very bad as investors are losing confidence on business here. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia, he added, has a strong \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  foundation such as natural resources and it has also made a remarkable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  progress. \par \par \uc2  He cited that global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospect would in the long term is dominated by technology and productivity but terrorism impact has taken the fruit they have brought, though a little. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, he reminded global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would face bad impact arising from trade and migration as well as \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  terror. In conclusion, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  factor still covers globally. \par \par \uc2  He then referred to IMF report through World \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Outlook, which predicts moderate world \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Such condition could only be achieved with good \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which focus on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamental recovery. \par \par \uc2  The world \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is projected to stay at about 2.8%. This year growth would stay the same as mentioned in April projection. Meanhwile next year growth is estimated to drop to level 3.7%. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery in Asia has showed greater than expected development, as reflected in the increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the region thanks to increasing domestic demand. (aph). \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020021021dyal0005m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
