\par\par \b \uc2  Chaotic Indonesia is waiting for 'messiah'. \b0\par\par\uc2 864 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 November 2002\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  6 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Satish Mishra, Head United Nations Support, Facility for Indonesian Recovey, Jakarta, satish.mishra@undp.org \par \par \uc2  These are confusing times. Indonesia is a country praised for its religious tolerance. Yet it is rocked by religious and ethnic strife. For a quarter of a century it was the home of one of the world's great \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  miracles. Today it is in the midst of its deepest \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. Until only five years ago, it was ruled by a proud military, supporting a single autocrat. Today, power is dispersed between the executive and the parliament and between central and regional government. \par \par \uc2  Only yesterday, foreign business and foreign personnel were welcomed as the harbingers of technology and enterprise. Today, they are suspected and feared as the precursors of a new global Imperium. Until recently, the Indonesian worker was thought as hard working and disciplined. Today, he is accused of being both unruly and unproductive. Only a short time ago, the world seemed to be knocking at Indonesia's door looking for opportunities for new business and new deals. Today, investors fly to safety. \par \par \uc2  Yesterday's miracle and yesterday's political order seem to have been consigned to the warehouse of fond relics and historical memorabilia. \par \par \uc2  Is it any wonder that "\b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 " represents the defining characteristic of the Indonesian national psyche? This \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  is combined with a feeling of powerlessness. Around half of Indonesia's 210 million people live on the edge of survival. Thousands stream into the cities in search for jobs and a future. In some such as Jakarta, they see new construction and new cars. They see shopping malls filled with beautiful things and equally beautiful, made-up women. They wonder why they can no longer make ends meet when so many have so much. As another month of Ramadan draws near, the city of Jakarta considers shutting the doors to new migrants coming to the city looking for work. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and powerlessness is a dangerous cocktail. It is especially dangerous when it comes on the heels of a generation of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and expanding job opportunities. The danger is compounded when \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is followed by sudden collapse and a feeling of national humiliation. This combination of humiliation, powerlessness and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  has spawned its own demons. Often demons such as these have devoured not only their own societies but much of the world around them. The history of so many dictatorships is the history of frustrated \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  hopes. \par \par \uc2  The prolonged \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown, the demise of established institutions and of familiar ways of doing things has led to a hunger for certainty. This is reflected in the frequent references to a strong leader who will provide order and certainty. It is also reflected in an open lamentation that Indonesia's new political system has failed to generate the firmness and political will to deal with jobs, foreigners, big business, military, trade unions, national unity and Uncle Sam. \par \par \uc2  You can take your own pick driven by your own personal prejudices. Taken against this stream of emotion and frustration democracy is often seen to be a luxury only the rich countries can afford. For many, growth first; democracy later, seems to be the only way out of the current impasse. This is a widely prevalent view shared by both Indonesian and foreigner alike. \par \par \uc2  History is never as simple as that. Societies might elect presidents. But they do not choose benevolent dictatorships. Autocracies are foisted. They represent instruments of control and privilege. They constrain and contain, not liberate and encourage. A preference for dictatorship is a sad obsession. It ignores the evidence of history. Look for a Soeharto and you might find a Mobutu or Amin. Equate order and discipline with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. You might end with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  collapse and ruin. Search for national unity within the confines of military supremacy. You might find instead latent dissent and open rebellion. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crises and collapses are divisive times. They exacerbate social stresses and fault-lines. They destroy trust and social capital. The great task of the recovery is to rebuild this capital, to heal open wounds, to convince the citizen that the costs of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  demise will be shared by everyone in a socially just way. \par \par \uc2  Social justice has to be a building block of recovery. It cannot be a mere footnote to growth oriented policies. Doubtless growth and a return to prosperity might ease the cultural and political shock of Indonesia's systemic transition. But, the secret of future stable growth lies in a direct approach to social divisions. Growth before democracy is a false doctrine. Democracy is a tool for a socially-just sharing of the burdens of hard and divisive times. Without a new social consensus, sustained growth along with the benevolent dictator is but a wistful dream of the desperate. The new \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  literature on the link between democratic governance and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth presents an important component of the logic of democracy. \par \par \uc2  Part two of this article explores this underlying logic of democracy and outlines some crucial next steps in the Indonesian transition. \par \par \uc2  The opinions expressed in this article are strictly personal. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020021104dyb4000ba\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
