\par\par \b \uc2  Business revival key to nation's security. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,039 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 November 2002\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  7 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Wimar Witoelar, InterMatrix Communications, Jakarta, wimar@witoelar.com \par \par \uc2  As Indonesia licks its wounds form the nation's latest tragedy, the outside world increases its pressure not just on potential terrorists, but on anyone who happens to be circumstantially linked to the al-Qaeda and the Jamaah Islamiyah. They are not our only problem. The world should know domestic terrorists have plagued us for a long time. As the professor Jeffrey Winters enumerated in his recent article Did the al-Qaeda really do it?, six bombs were detonated in 1998, nine in 1999, 20 in 2000, and seven in 2001. \par \par \uc2  Not too many people wept for Indonesia internationally then as they do now for Bali. It is actually the same show of terror made worse by the addition of international victims which puts it on an international stage. \par \par \uc2  But while New York after Sept. 11 received a huge outpouring of support and sympathy, Indonesia receives recrimination and suspicion even as we are still weeping at our huge loss. Travelers are advised to stay away from Indonesia while they were not told to stay away from New York. A scaremonger in Brisbane's Courier-Mail even described Jakarta as a "city of fear". Actually the most fearful thing about Jakarta is that it may be pushed off the map before people get a chance to know its chaotic charm. \par \par \uc2  Wile international terror is still under investigation, international business has condemned Indonesia as a hopeless place to do business. We are losing big in the international \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations and media game. As long as the al-Qaeda elude George W. Bush, we get pushed on a downward spiral with the collapse of our international business image. \par \par \uc2  Singapore might complain about being put on the Australian government's travel advisory list as a dangerous place to visit, but at least their business credibility is still intact. They just reached an agreement with Australia on a free trade deal, which could generate hundreds of millions of dollars in export revenue for both sides. The Australian Trade Minister sent a clear signal that Australia is going to remain there and increase their engagement throughout Southeast Asia. They are negotiating with Thailand and remain open to offers to negotiate similar deals. Is Indonesia on their agenda? Probably not, to put it succinctly. \par \par \uc2  At the ASEAN summit in Cambodia, Japan will tantalize Southeast Asian leaders with talk of free-trade agreements and closer relations. Japanese Prime Minister Junichiro Koizumi has announced that the proposed trade agreement will be high on the agenda when he meets with ASEAN leaders on Tuesday. We have no idea how our own President Megawati Soekarnoputri will perform; we do not expect overly joyous news. \par \par \uc2  It is highly \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  whether Indonesia will be able to share the recovery of international business. But this is not exclusively related to the terrorism issue. We have many foreign business people still operating in Indonesia, and multinational firms committed to stay for years, even decades. They feel quite safe, at least normal, in their everyday rounds. \par \par \uc2  These people make up the international business community that we should court. A management guru at IBM once revealed a study that showed gaining new customers costs 12 times as expensive as retaining old ones. We have so many international names here that mentioning them would make this article look like an advertisement. But they are pressed against the wall when their bosses and owners ask back home ask why they still have hope in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  For business people who have long experience and good knowledge of Indonesia, the issue is not terrorism, which has turned global. They are facing a more serious problem, a truly debilitating disease in the form of an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  business environment, poorly articulated policies left undefended. The business-political system leaves the reform attempts vulnerable to cooption and sabotage. \par \par \uc2  The battle for clean government and good corporate governance has always been difficult but now it has become a losing one. Legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  has reached the level of celebrated cases. Other crises are brewing in the background. There is a prevalence of regional insubordination to central authority. Further problems come from political opportunists who exploit \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  ignorance about foreign investment and privatization. \par \par \uc2  In terms of business recovery, these are the real terrorists whom the international war on terror leave unscathed. When you look at the due of corruption and violence, corruption is left unchecked by our government while perpetrators of violence are getting merciful treatment by foreign governments eager to work with the military. \par \par \uc2  It is disappointing to hear of groups who are fishing in troubled waters. Instead of strengthening the market \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , they seek to stop the government privatization program through class action suits. These misguided ideas are expressed in demonstrations and unilateral declarations against legal authority. There is wry humor here considering that the government has not been particularly forceful about privatization anyway. \par \par \uc2  Populist politicians play to the uninformed \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  by depicting privatization as loss of local ownership and international acquisition as a takeover by foreigners to send Indonesians deeper into poverty. They draw parallel lines of xenophobia along political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  themes. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  stands to increase their chances against poverty through privatization. The market takes control away from bureaucrats and corrupt management. That is why these groups of people drag their feet on privatization. They are worried about their own privileged positions, not the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  interest. The government would be much less in debt if their privatization were pursued with more energy. In fact, the reason the national \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  faces problems is because privatization targets for cash revenues are not being met. \par \par \uc2  It takes a lot of patience and sensitivity to explain these things, but it has to be started. The worry now is that Indonesia is going to be trampled in the world hunt for terrorists, and that business will suffer. We should position ourselves such that we all join hands in making the world safe from terrorists. \par \par \uc2  But it is business recovery that will make Indonesia a better place for its people. And it would make it less fertile for hate-spreading radicals and scare mongering overseas writers. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020021105dyb500061\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  The Fed cut interest, IHSG not affected. \b0\par\par\uc2 533 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 November 2002\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  A number of stock analysts believed The Fed's recent decision of cutting interest rate wouldn't significantly affect composite index in Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) as investors focus more on domestic factor such as Bali bombing rather than external one. \par \par \uc2  An analyst from PT Danareksa Research Institute Ferry Latuhihin said trauma from the bombing still exists that The Fed decision of lowering the interest rate wouldn't too much affect index in JSX. \par \par \uc2  The US \b \highlight22\uc2 Central Bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  (The Fed) decided to cut interest rate by 50 basic points from 1.75% down to 1.25%. The decrease is the first to make this year and also is the lowest level in the past four decades. \par \par \uc2  Despite the bombing, there is still another factor of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in rupiah exchange rate, of which currently stands at Rp 9.210 against US dollar. \par \par \uc2  Market players are now giving more concern to security condition rather than interest rate cut as they think that it is just an instrument to arise positive sentiment in the short term. In contrary market sees the sharp decrease as a sign that US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is facing a serious problem. \par \par \uc2  Another analyst from PT Danareksa Desimon was also of the same opinion saying that the interest rate cut would not bring direct effect on the bonds market. \par \par \uc2  "Bonds market in rupiah denomination wouldn't feel impact of the interest rate cut but not to bonds in US$, which would experience piece hike," he said. \par \par \uc2  The interest rate decrease should be seen to the decrease of SBI interest rate. \par \par \uc2  "If inflation is under control and SBI decreases, the impact might surface in bond market. It means bonds price would increase," he said. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile Mirza Adityaswara, head of Research of Bahan Securities spoke of different opinion stating that index in JSX would however be shadowed by Dow Jones index. \par \par \uc2  According to him the decision was made to keep US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery momentum at place amid the probable US-Iraq war. \par \par \uc2  "There's nothing wrong collecting blue chip share while share price is decreasing," he explained. \par \par \uc2  Break through 400 \par \par \uc2  He further predicted that the composite index would break through the level of 400, even might reach 480 next year following the rise of Dow Jones share coming along with US recovering \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The low index recorded during the last quarter could actually happen all year. But the thing is this year decrease is more drastic compared to the previous years, because of the Bali bombing. \par \par \uc2  "Index only dropped by 12% when May riot 1998 occurred, but it even go up higher reaching 14% in the wake of the Bali bombing, plunged to the lowest level of 325," he said yesterday at a breakfasting of Bahan Securities. \par \par \uc2  He predicted index would strengthen in the first semester next year, ranging at between 440 and 480. But in the second semester, there usually comes clashes, especially prior to the General election 2004, that index might drop to level 400 up to 450. \par \par \uc2  He added, three weeks after the bombing market responded positively to the anti terrorist \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  government has taken as it did not trigger domestic political fluctuation.(08/shm/dj). \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020021108dyb800003\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
