\par\par \b \uc2  An unstrategic plan. \b0\par\par\uc2 779 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 November 2002\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  6 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Big projects begin with dreams, some say. But this slogan is apparently not true for Jakarta Governor Sutiyoso, who has just revealed his latest dream. \par \par \uc2  This is to develop Jakarta in an idealistic manner via the 2002-2007 Strategic Plan, which addresses eight major issues, the draft of which he presented to the City Council plenary session on Tuesday. The council is expected to approve the plan so that it can become a set of bylaws. \par \par \uc2  Frankly speaking, the 250-page draft contains nothing special except for the idealistic dreams of an official bombarded by criticism for lacking vision and initiative. \par \par \uc2  A councillor has said that the Strategic Plan is too prescriptive. \par \par \uc2  The plan contains prescriptions and ideals, without the concrete steps to achieve them. \par \par \uc2  It is clear that Sutiyoso has simply listed and recorded all the problems in a comprehensive manner. What he terms the matrix of problems, however, does not promise any clear action to resolve them. \par \par \uc2  Each matrix has four columns: "the course and the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ", "the strategy" (which comprises normative steps), the "program" (which is a normative plan) and "indicators of performance" as a result of the plan's implementation, which is no more than a list of ideals. \par \par \uc2  In short, Sutiyoso has been very capable of making an inventory of the problems, but fails to explain how the plan's noble intentions can be achieved. \par \par \uc2  Take the matrix on natural resources and the environment. "The course and the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 " is managing natural resources and enhancing efforts on conservation, rehabilitation and the saving of natural resources by the application of environmentally friendly technology, especially in mining and energy, and in water in residential areas. \par \par \uc2  "The strategy" is to optimize efforts on conservation, rehabilitation and saving of natural resources through adequate information to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , improving coordination among concerned institutions in charge of underground utilities and improving law enforcement in the case of improper and excessive use of groundwater. \par \par \uc2  "The programs (on groundwater preservation) are developing the sources (of groundwater) and indicators of performance are: first, better control of the use of groundwater by government institutions, businesses and the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; second, increasing the level of groundwater; third, increasing groundwater deposition in line with the increase in the number of artesian wells, injection wells and the construction of reservoirs; fourth, availability of data and information on groundwater relating to the (annual) dry season." \par \par \uc2  People might be puzzled after reading one of the many matrices in the draft Strategic Plan. They give no clear indication on how to implement all the dreams and promises. Sutiyoso also fails to mention the proposed target beneficiaries of the plan and the deadline. \par \par \uc2  We are curious to know what Sutiyoso really means by "developing groundwater sources" as the only program to optimally use natural resources (groundwater in this case). Isn't it a very straightforward issue that a first-year high school student could easily understand? \par \par \uc2  In this way the Army lieutenant general - again - has failed to demonstrate his ability to promote improvement of the city, despite the fact that he now holds the post of governor for a second (consecutive) term, from 2002 to 2007. \par \par \uc2  With the Strategic Plan Sutiyoso merely proves himself to be a "publicity seeker", demonstrating his increasing unpopularity since his reelection campaign in August this year. \par \par \uc2  Councillor Haim Hamidi of the National Mandate Party (PAN) has said that Sutiyoso deliberately framed the Strategic Plan in such a way as to avoid running the risk of its being rejected by the council. \par \par \uc2  If so, Sutiyoso's Strategic Plan reminds us of the systematic Five-Year Development Plans(Repelita) produced under former president Soeharto. \par \par \uc2  Using all the powers at his disposal, Soeharto managed to introduce his wide-ranging Repelita, which became an effective political tool for him and his supporters to retain both power and position. The first Repelita was followed by the second and then by the third, etc., until he resigned in 1998. \par \par \uc2  The ball is now in the hands of the City Council. We suggest that the council be patient and careful in studying the draft. Sutiyoso has said that revision is still possible; therefore, it is imperative that the council study the draft, despite the fact that Sutiyoso has claimed its preparation has involved experts, intellectuals and scholars from a variety of universities. \par \par \uc2  The council must be extra-careful before it approves the draft to become a set of bylaws. We hope that the plan produced by Sutiyoso will not lead us deeper into more \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Jakartans, fed up by \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 , security, social and legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , might simply go "insane" at Sutiyoso's strategic, or unstrategic, plan. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020021115dybf0000b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
