\par\par \b \uc2  'Purified' Bali looks ahead to recovery. \b0\par\par\uc2 608 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 November 2002\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Damaso Reyes, Contributor, Jimbaran, Bali \par \par \uc2  The ritual purification on Friday has marked new ground for Bali to recover, putting the deadly blast behind it. \par \par \uc2  Despite President Megawati Soekarnoputri's absence from the elaborate ceremony, the mood and determination of all parties concerned about Bali's restoration were evident. \par \par \uc2  The Bali Tourism Board along with the Office of the State Minister of Culture and Tourism as well as the private sector have come together in an effort to create a new brand identity for Bali in the wake of the Oct. 12 terrorist attack which has scarred the islands reputation as a safe holiday destination. \par \par \uc2  The result is a print and television campaign: "Bali: Get into it". \par \par \uc2  "We in Bali will never surrender to the terrorists," declared Minister of Tourism and Culture I Gede Ardika at the press conference to announce the effort. "Yes, they have been able to destroy buildings, shops and cars but they will never destroy the spirit of Bali." \par \par \uc2  The rebranding comes in the wake of a precipitous drop in tourist arrivals to what was once Asia's most popular vacation destination. Worst case scenarios predict that hundreds of thousands of Balinese who depend on the tourism sector could lose their livelihood. \par \par \uc2  "We have purified our island. We have made it secure," said Putu Antara, chairman of the Bali Tourism Board. "Now it is time to help those who depend on the tourist industry," he added. \par \par \uc2  Since the purification ceremony on Friday, there has been much talk of looking to the future, one that appears increasingly \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  after several nations have issued travel advisories suggesting non-essential visits to Indonesia and Bali be avoided in the wake of the bomb attacks. \par \par \uc2  The attack led to a 75 percent drop in holidaymakers to the island, and is likely to force Indonesia to lower its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target of four percent this year. \par \par \uc2  In additional to a new logo and catch phrase, a slick new television commercial has been created. Due to the lack of funds it will only be shown on a pro bono basis by local television stations. It is difficult to say if the message will be heard by foreign tourists already inundated by advertising campaigns of other Southeast Asian nations which outspend Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Also on the agenda is a possible change in the current visa free facility that Indonesia grants most foreigners which gives them a free short stay visa on arrival without applying for a visa at an embassy or consulate. Minister Ardika stressed that the discussions within the government were ongoing and that no decision had been made. If and when a change would be made he said that it would take at least six months to implement. \par \par \uc2  Ardika said the current discussion would be to change the current system into one in which nations would fall into three categories. \par \par \uc2  The first category groups nations that would still enjoy the visa free facility. Those would most likely be nations which already offer Indonesian citizens a reciprocal facility on arrival. The second would be a group of nations where tourists would have to pay for a visa on arrival. The third would be nations whose citizens would have to apply and be granted visas before arrival. \par \par \uc2  Observers say if foreign nationals are forced to pay or apply for visas it could hurt the faltering tourism sector of which \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  travelers or backpackers make up a significant percentage. These are the visitors most likely to still come despite travel advisories but are more sensitive to price increases and difficulties in processing visas. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020021117dybi0000g\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Program loan up US$300 million -  \highlight22\uc2 Stimulus \highlight\uc2  Rp10.5 trillion. \b0\par\par\uc2 478 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 November 2002\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Financing source from foreign loan for next year state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is projected to increase by US$300 million at the least following the increase in development \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  by Rp10.5 trillion. \par \par \uc2  The state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  committee meeting last night decided that state revenue is projected to reach Rp336.155 trillion with state \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp370.591 trillion, resulting a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp34.436 trillion or 1.78% of GDP. \par \par \uc2  Development \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to increase by Rp10.5 trillion from Rp54.449 trillion previously up to Rp65.129 trillion. \par \par \uc2  "This increase is expected to serve as \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Priyo Budi Santoso, the committee member said when delivering the meeting conclusion last night. But the decision requires approval from the \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  Committee plenum. \par \par \uc2  Government would rely on domestic source of Rp22.45 trillion to finance the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  despite foreign source of Rp11.98 trillion. \par \par \uc2  The committee Chairman Abdullah Zainie said the gross foreign loan is targeted at Rp29.2 trillion comprising program loan of Rp10.3 trillion and project loan of Rp18.9 trillion. \par \par \uc2  "Program loan increase by US$300 million while the project loan by Rp600 billion," he said. \par \par \uc2  He added the new \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  scenario is expected to bring about more \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2 , primarily from the development \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , to boost growth in real sector that the projected 4% \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth could be reached. \par \par \uc2  Separately an economist from Indef Dradjad H. Wibowo said the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  could only bring the expected result if it were introduced at the right place and the right time. \par \par \uc2  According to him the \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  could be used in February or March 2003 the latest otherwise government would lose the momentum for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  "\b \highlight22\uc2 Stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be absorbed by political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  ahead of general election 2004." \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  should be given to infrastructure and workers based industry such as textile, electronics, wood, garment, and shoe industry. \par \par \uc2  "Those are the ailing industries. Textile industry could even suffer from drop of 40%," he said. \par \par \uc2  Revenue increase \par \par \uc2  On the other part Zainie noted of the increase in revenue of Rp15 trillion reaped and about Rp6 trillion of which would be used to cover the unfulfilled \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue target. \par \par \uc2  "The other 9 trillion would be used to finance development and \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 ." \par \par \uc2  There is also probability that government might use the \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\