\par\par \b \uc2  Govt fears backlash if IBRA debtors released - Experts. \b0\par\par\uc2 557 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 November 2002\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  3 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The government's indecision over who should sign the documents to drop criminal charges against former bankers who had abused trillions of rupiah in state loans showed that officials feared their decision could spark a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  backlash, experts have said. \par \par \uc2  They warned that attempts to avoid responsibility also called into question the credibility of any decision to release the ex-bankers. \par \par \uc2  "I suspect everybody is just trying to avoid responsibility," said lawyer Frans H. Winarta on Wednesday. \par \par \uc2  Controversy has returned over the handling of former bankers who abused some Rp 138 trillion (about US$15.28 billion) in government funds and violated banking regulations following the 1997 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  Their actions have annually cost the government trillions of rupiah in interest payments on bonds that were issued to safeguard their banks from collapsing. \par \par \uc2  Under the shareholders settlement program, the ex-bankers agreed to repay the abused funds in return for not facing prosecution. \par \par \uc2  The agreement was signed by the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA), which is in charge of recouping the lost funds. \par \par \uc2  IBRA recommended on Monday that the government release four of the 35 former bankers, reasoning that they had settled their debts. \par \par \uc2  But a decision over who should approve that move has not been made. The government said that by early December President Megawati Soekarnoputri would appoint the officials who would sign the release and discharge documents. \par \par \uc2  Signing the papers, however, means that those officials could be later held accountable by the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  who might disapprove of the decision, said Frans. \par \par \uc2  He said that since it was IBRA who signed the settlement program with the bankers, the agency should also be the one signing the documents. \par \par \uc2  IBRA chairman Syafruddin Temengung suggested on Tuesday that the decision should rest with the Coordinating Ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the Attorney General's Office. \par \par \uc2  IBRA's overseer, the Financial Sector \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Committee (FSPC), however, might not approve of any of its recommendations yet. \par \par \uc2  Quoted by detik.com, FSPC chairman Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Dorodjatun Kuntjoro-Jakti said the FSPC would discuss IBRA's recommendations and forward them to the Cabinet meeting for President Megawati to decide. \par \par \uc2  "This is so typical. Officials first wrestle for power but when it comes to taking responsibility for the power they have, everyone just wants to avoid it," said banking analyst Lin Che Wei. \par \par \uc2  He said the release and discharge documents were supposed to be signed at the same time that IBRA signed the shareholders settlement program with the former bankers. \par \par \uc2  The fact that nobody did, he said, showed that the previous administration knew of the trouble their signatures might cause. \par \par \uc2  However, delaying a decision is not an option anymore as for most debtors, their settlement program is nearing the deadline. \par \par \uc2  IBRA's proposal earlier this year to extend the program by another 10 years was voted down under a wave of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  protests. \par \par \uc2  Che Wei added that the officials' \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  showed that they were unsure if the decision to release the debtors would stand up against \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  suspicion that the debtors were cheating on their repayments. \par \par \uc2  Analysts have long suspected that the debtors had made minimal repayments and surrendered assets, which they later bought back from IBRA at heavily discounted prices using third parties. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020021121dybl00005\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
